<title>The !kau who brought home his own flesh as food</title>
<summary>A tale of the Early Race about the !khau lizard, who brings home his own flesh as food so that his wife will think he has brought home a Quagga. Eventually the wife tells their child to go out with his father and see what flesh he is bringing and the child sees his father go into a whirlwind and come out rolling his flesh in a net. The woman throws away the husband&apos;s flesh and leaves him for her father&apos;s people.</summary><comments>1) See also <i>Song of the !kau&apos;s child</i>, 2) p.7113v:  |han≠kass&apos;o heard this story from his mother (|xabbi-an), 3) p.7119opp: about an insect, 4) p.7119v: see <i>Aquilae&apos;s water</i>, 5) p.7139v: how people swallow raw liver, 6) See also <i>The death of the !kau (a lizard of the genus Agama</i>) and <i>Song of the !kau&apos;s child</i>, and <i>Remarks by |han≠kass&apos;o on the preceding story (The death of the !kau</i>), 7) This story is found in Books VIII-12 and Book VIII-13</comments><date>29 June 1878 (started)</date><storypages>7114-7118, 7119-7156</storypages><category>History (Early Race)</category><author>|han≠kass'o (Klein Jantje) (VIII)</author><keyword><kw>Early Race</kw><subkw>food eaten by</subkw></keyword>
